03:19:37,000 --> 03:19:47,000
So we have a pivot position in every column of l which means we have a pivot position in every row of l since l is square.

2199
03:19:47,000 --> 03:19:55,000
And if there's a pivot position in every row then that means that the columns span rn.

2200
03:19:55,000 --> 03:20:00,000
Alright let's talk about invertible linear transformations.

2201
03:20:00,000 --> 03:20:08,000
Let's suppose we have a linear transformation t from rn to rn that's defined by the matrix a.

2202
03:20:08,000 --> 03:20:12,000
So a here would be n by n.

2203
03:20:12,000 --> 03:20:17,000
Alright for any x we can compute ax right?

2204
03:20:17,000 --> 03:20:23,000
For any x we can compute t of x or a times x.

2205
03:20:23,000 --> 03:20:26,000
Let's think about going backwards though.

2206
03:20:26,000 --> 03:20:39,000
Suppose you have some b and you would like to know is there a unique vector x such that ax equals b?

2207
03:20:39,000 --> 03:20:52,000
Okay so think of b as being in the co-domain and we want to go backwards to see what x mapped to that b.

2208
03:20:52,000 --> 03:20:57,000
Well this works if t is both one to one and onto.

2209
03:20:57,000 --> 03:21:10,000
Okay so for us to be able to go backwards and find out what x mapped to b we can do that if we know that t is one to one and onto.

2210
03:21:10,000 --> 03:21:12,000
Okay so why is that?

2211
03:21:12,000 --> 03:21:21,000
Well if t is onto then that means that every b and rn is mapped to by at least one x.

2212
03:21:21,000 --> 03:21:25,000
Every b is mapped to by at least one x.

2213
03:21:25,000 --> 03:21:31,000
So that means that if we go backward there's an x to go back to.

2214
03:21:31,000 --> 03:21:38,000
If it's one to one then that means that every b is mapped to by at most one x.

2215
03:21:38,000 --> 03:21:41,000
Every b is mapped to by at most one x.

2216
03:21:41,000 --> 03:21:47,000
So that means that if we can go backwards there's only one vector to go backwards to.

2217
03:21:47,000 --> 03:21:51,000
We don't have multiple vectors mapping to the same b.

2218
03:21:51,000 --> 03:22:00,000
So if you put those two things together t is one to one and onto then every b is mapped to by exactly one x.

2219
03:22:00,000 --> 03:22:04,000
Which means there's a unique solution.

2220
03:22:04,000 --> 03:22:06,000
So how do we find that x?

2221
03:22:06,000 --> 03:22:12,000
Given a particular vector b how do we find out what x mapped to it?

2222
03:22:12,000 --> 03:22:26,000
Well we need to solve ax equals b and the way to do that if we know that a is invertible is to simply multiply a inverse times b.

2223
03:22:26,000 --> 03:22:33,000
So the matrix that defines the inverse transformation t inverse is simply a inverse.

2224
03:22:33,000 --> 03:22:50,000
So a takes you forward from x you multiply a times x to get b in the co-domain to go backwards to reverse that.

2225
03:22:50,000 --> 03:22:53,000
You multiply by a inverse.

2226
03:22:53,000 --> 03:23:00,000
So t is defined by a, t inverse is defined by a inverse.

2227
03:23:01,000 --> 03:23:04,000
Another way to look at it is this.

2228
03:23:04,000 --> 03:23:14,000
Under what conditions does there exist a unique vector x such that ax equals b for every b in our n?

2229
03:23:14,000 --> 03:23:25,000
When can we know that the system ax equals b is always consistent and always has a unique solution?

2230
03:23:25,000 --> 03:23:30,000
Well it's consistent if there's a pivot position in every row of a.

2231
03:23:30,000 --> 03:23:37,000
Ax equals b is consistent for every b if there's a pivot position in every row of a.

2232
03:23:37,000 --> 03:23:42,000
And if the solution is unique then there has to be no free variables.

2233
03:23:42,000 --> 03:23:46,000
So that means there has to be a pivot position in every column of a.

2234
03:23:46,000 --> 03:23:51,000
So backing up it's consistent.

2235
03:23:51,000 --> 03:23:55,000
If it's consistent for every b we have to have a pivot position in every row.

2236
03:23:55,000 --> 03:24:03,000
If there's a unique solution then that means we have no free variables so we have to have a pivot position in every column.

2237
03:24:03,000 --> 03:24:12,000
So t of x equals ax is invertible when a has a pivot position in every row and column.

2238
03:24:12,000 --> 03:24:19,000
i.e. when a has n pivot positions i.e. when a is invertible.

2239
03:24:26,000 --> 03:24:29,000
Okay we're going to talk about determinants.

2240
03:24:29,000 --> 03:24:39,000
The determinant of a matrix is just a scalar value that is associated with any square matrix.

2241
03:24:39,000 --> 03:24:44,000
So we only talk about the determinant of a square matrix.

2242
03:24:44,000 --> 03:24:58,000
The notation is d e t of a or sometimes you see it with a looks like absolute value of a with the vertical bars around a.

2243
03:24:58,000 --> 03:25:05,000
We've actually already seen the determinant in the 2 by 2 case.

2244
03:25:05,000 --> 03:25:13,000
If we have a is just this generic matrix a b c d then the determinant of a is a times d minus b times c.

2245
03:25:13,000 --> 03:25:21,000
And we've seen that because we saw that in the little formula for the inverse of a 2 by 2.

2246
03:25:21,000 --> 03:25:27,000
So remember we multiplied by 1 over a d minus b c.

2247
03:25:27,000 --> 03:25:31,000
So we're multiplying by 1 over the determinant of the matrix.

2248
03:25:31,000 --> 03:25:38,000
And then we kind of rearrange the terms and negate couple to get the inverse of a matrix.

2249
03:25:38,000 --> 03:25:50,000
So notice that at least in the case of a 2 by 2 matrix we can see that the inverse exists when the determinant of the matrix is not equal to 0.

2250
03:25:50,000 --> 03:25:57,000
Here in this case if a d minus b c is equal to 0 then a inverse does not exist.

2251
03:25:57,000 --> 03:26:01,000
And it turns out that this is true for any square matrix.

2252
03:26:01,000 --> 03:26:09,000
If the determinant is not equal to 0 that means the matrix is invertible and it's invertible then the determinant is not equal to 0.

2253
03:26:09,000 --> 03:26:19,000
So this is actually another installment in the invertible matrix theorem which we had from section 2.3.

2254
03:26:19,000 --> 03:26:28,000
So determinant of a not equal to 0 is logically equivalent to a is invertible.

2255
03:26:28,000 --> 03:26:36,000
Alright if we move up beyond a 2 by 2 there's no nice formula for competing the determinant like there was for a 2 by 2.

2256
03:26:36,000 --> 03:26:40,000
And we use a method called cofactor expansion.

2257
03:26:40,000 --> 03:26:47,000
And this method works for any size matrix 3 by 3 on up.

2258
03:26:47,000 --> 03:26:52,000
In this method we have to choose a row or column to expand about.

2259
03:26:52,000 --> 03:26:56,000
That's what we call it. We're going to choose a row or column to expand about.

2260
03:26:56,000 --> 03:27:05,000
You'll see as we go on that it's advantageous to choose a row or column that has the most zeros in it because that eliminates some of the terms.

2261
03:27:05,000 --> 03:27:12,000
But for our first cut here I'm just going to expand about the first row.

2262
03:27:12,000 --> 03:27:19,000
And I've kind of color coded this to make it easier for you to see where the terms come from.

2263
03:27:19,000 --> 03:27:25,000
Okay so if we expand about the first row we start with the first entry which is the 5.

2264
03:27:25,000 --> 03:27:37,000
And then we multiply 5 by the determinant of the matrix that you're left with if you eliminate the row or column that contains the 5.

2265
03:27:37,000 --> 03:27:47,000
So if you eliminate the first row and eliminate the first column then you see that you have this little 2 by 2 matrix that's sitting right here.

2266
03:27:47,000 --> 03:27:50,000
And so we're going to take the determinant of that.

2267
03:27:50,000 --> 03:27:55,000
And then we move over to the next entry in the first row which is the 2.

2268
03:27:55,000 --> 03:28:04,000
And we multiply that by the determinant of the matrix that you get if you eliminate the first row and the second column.

2269
03:28:04,000 --> 03:28:07,000
Okay the row and the column containing the 2.

2270
03:28:07,000 --> 03:28:13,000
So we're left with the 0, 2 here and the negative 5, 7 here.

2271
03:28:13,000 --> 03:28:16,000
Okay so that's how we get this matrix here.

2272
03:28:16,000 --> 03:28:19,000
Then we continue moving across the first row.

2273
03:28:19,000 --> 03:28:28,000
Then we've got a 4 and we multiply 4 by the matrix that you get if you eliminate the first row and the third column.

2274
03:28:28,000 --> 03:28:30,000
Okay eliminate the row and the column containing the 4.

2275
03:28:30,000 --> 03:28:35,000
So you're left with this little 2 by 2 here, 0, 3, 2, negative 4.

2276
03:28:35,000 --> 03:28:37,000
And that's what we have here.

2277
03:28:37,000 --> 03:28:40,000
Now notice I haven't combined these terms at all.

2278
03:28:40,000 --> 03:28:42,000
I've just written them out here.

2279
03:28:42,000 --> 03:28:47,000
And that's because there's a method for combining the terms.

2280
03:28:47,000 --> 03:28:50,000
Okay we have to put them together somehow.

2281
03:28:50,000 --> 03:29:01,000
And basically you apply a coefficient to each term which is negative 1 to the i plus j.

2282
03:29:01,000 --> 03:29:07,000
Where i and j are the row and column indices corresponding to that term.

2283
03:29:07,000 --> 03:29:13,000
So if we look back up to the 5, 5 came from row 1 column 1.

2284
03:29:13,000 --> 03:29:18,000
So the coefficient that we put in front of that term is minus 1 to the 1 plus 1.

2285
03:29:18,000 --> 03:29:21,000
Because 5 came from row 1 column 1.

2286
03:29:21,000 --> 03:29:29,000
Alright then for the next term, this one, the 2, the blue term, came from this entry here.

2287
03:29:29,000 --> 03:29:33,000
The 2 is in the first row second column.

2288
03:29:33,000 --> 03:29:37,000
So that means the coefficient here is minus 1 to the 1 plus 2.

2289
03:29:37,000 --> 03:29:41,000
Row 1 column 2, that's where the 1 plus 2 comes from.

2290
03:29:41,000 --> 03:29:48,000
And then for the 4, the green term, it's in the first row third column.

2291
03:29:48,000 --> 03:29:56,000
So we have minus 1 to the 1 plus 3 as the coefficient in front of that term.

2292
03:29:56,000 --> 03:30:04,000
And so if we multiply and add, then we get minus 1 to the 1 plus 1.

2293
03:30:04,000 --> 03:30:06,000
So that's minus 1 squared.

2294
03:30:06,000 --> 03:30:08,000
So that's just plus 1 times 5.

2295
03:30:08,000 --> 03:30:10,000
So we bring down 5.

2296
03:30:10,000 --> 03:30:13,000
And the determinant here, remember it's just the crisscross.

2297
03:30:13,000 --> 03:30:17,000
3 times 7 minus negative 4 times negative 5.

2298
03:30:17,000 --> 03:30:19,000
So that's what we have here.

2299
03:30:19,000 --> 03:30:22,000
Alright, then moving on here to the blue.

2300
03:30:22,000 --> 03:30:24,000
We got minus 1 to the 1 plus 2.

2301
03:30:24,000 --> 03:30:26,000
That's minus 1 cubed.

2302
03:30:26,000 --> 03:30:29,000
So that's negative 1 times 2.

2303
03:30:29,000 --> 03:30:32,000
Gives us the negative 2 here.

2304
03:30:32,000 --> 03:30:38,000
Times the determinant which is 0 times 7 minus 2 times negative 5.

2305
03:30:38,000 --> 03:30:43,000
Alright, then moving over to the next term, the green one comes from the 4.

2306
03:30:43,000 --> 03:30:45,000
And that's first row third column.

2307
03:30:45,000 --> 03:30:49,000
So that's the minus 1 to the 1 plus 3.

2308
03:30:49,000 --> 03:30:54,000
Which is minus 1 to the fourth, which is positive 1 times 4.

2309
03:30:54,000 --> 03:30:59,000
And so you get a plus 4 in front of that term.

2310
03:30:59,000 --> 03:31:05,000
Times the determinant which is 0 times negative 4 minus 2 times 3.

2311
03:31:05,000 --> 03:31:08,000
Alright, then combining a little more.

2312
03:31:08,000 --> 03:31:12,000
We got 21 minus 20 here.

2313
03:31:12,000 --> 03:31:14,000
Times 5.

2314
03:31:14,000 --> 03:31:17,000
Then we've got 0 plus 10.

2315
03:31:17,000 --> 03:31:19,000
So just a 10 there.

2316
03:31:19,000 --> 03:31:21,000
And then here's 0 minus 6.

2317
03:31:21,000 --> 03:31:23,000
So negative 6 there.

2318
03:31:23,000 --> 03:31:30,000
And we combine and we end up with negative 39 for the determinant of this matrix.

2319
03:31:30,000 --> 03:31:33,000
Okay, now just a little aside.

2320
03:31:33,000 --> 03:31:41,000
It's really not necessary to explicitly compute this minus 1 to the i plus j term every time.

2321
03:31:41,000 --> 03:31:44,000
If you just look, here's a 4 by 4.

2322
03:31:44,000 --> 03:31:49,000
Where I've put as the entries in the matrix just the row index plus the column index.

2323
03:31:49,000 --> 03:31:51,000
So 1, 1 position, we got 1 plus 1.

2324
03:31:51,000 --> 03:31:54,000
1, 2 position, 1 plus 2, and so forth.

2325
03:31:54,000 --> 03:31:58,000
So if we look at what that is, we end up with these numbers.

2326
03:31:58,000 --> 03:32:02,000
And remember we want minus 1 raised to each of these powers.

2327
03:32:02,000 --> 03:32:09,000
And so you can see since they all differ by one, going from one term to an adjacent term,

2328
03:32:09,000 --> 03:32:11,000
either in the same row or the same column,

2329
03:32:11,000 --> 03:32:15,000
you either go from an even number to an odd or an odd to an even.

2330
03:32:15,000 --> 03:32:21,000
So in any case, alternating terms are always going to have opposite signs.

2331
03:32:21,000 --> 03:32:26,000
And you always start off in the upper left with a plus, plus 1,

2332
03:32:26,000 --> 03:32:30,000
because that's minus 1 that the 1 plus 1 or minus 1 squared.

2333
03:32:30,000 --> 03:32:34,000
So you always know that the 1, 1 position is a plus term,

2334
03:32:34,000 --> 03:32:38,000
and then everything alternates after that.

2335
03:32:38,000 --> 03:32:40,000
So it's always plus, minus, plus, minus.

2336
03:32:40,000 --> 03:32:49,000
So if you know the sign that goes with the first term in the row or the column that you're expanding about,

2337
03:32:49,000 --> 03:32:53,000
then you only need to alternate terms after that.

2338
03:32:53,000 --> 03:32:56,000
So you always have this checkerboard patterns.

2339
03:32:56,000 --> 03:33:04,000
And you just need to alternate terms based on the sign of the position where you start.

2340
03:33:04,000 --> 03:33:09,000
So let's look at this matrix again.

2341
03:33:09,000 --> 03:33:14,000
It's the same one, but I'm going to expand about the second column this time,

2342
03:33:14,000 --> 03:33:16,000
just for something different.

2343
03:33:16,000 --> 03:33:21,000
Now, first note that the second column or the first entry there is the 2,

2344
03:33:21,000 --> 03:33:23,000
and it's in the 1, 2 position.

2345
03:33:23,000 --> 03:33:29,000
So minus 1 to the 1 plus 2, if you want to compete it like that, minus 1 cubed, that's a negative 1.

2346
03:33:29,000 --> 03:33:32,000
So this is a negative position here.

2347
03:33:32,000 --> 03:33:35,000
Or you can say, I always know that the 1, 1 position is a plus.

