3456
04:48:38,000 --> 04:48:45,000
Okay, we're continuing in section 4.1 with more about vector spaces.

3457
04:48:45,000 --> 04:49:07,000
And there's one way that we've talked about for finding if a set is a subspace of another vector space is to show that it satisfies the three properties that it contains the zero vector of the parent vector space.

3458
04:49:07,000 --> 04:49:14,000
It's closed under addition and it's closed under scalar multiplication.

3459
04:49:15,000 --> 04:49:23,000
So to show that a set is a subspace, then you can show that these three things hold.

3460
04:49:23,000 --> 04:49:28,000
Or to show that it's not a subspace, show that at least one of these does not hold.

3461
04:49:28,000 --> 04:49:36,000
But we have another method for showing that a set is a subspace.

3462
04:49:36,000 --> 04:49:47,000
And this doesn't work in all cases, but in some cases you can use this theorem and it makes life much easier because you don't have to go through and show those three properties hold.

3463
04:49:47,000 --> 04:50:04,000
So the theorem says if v1 through vp are vectors in some vector space v, then the span of v1 through vp is a subspace of v.

3464
04:50:04,000 --> 04:50:26,000
So what this says is that if we can write our set as the span of a finite set of vectors, right in this form, span of v1 through vp for some vectors, then automatically we can conclude that the set is a subspace.

3465
04:50:27,000 --> 04:50:29,000
So let's look at this example.

3466
04:50:29,000 --> 04:50:33,000
We have a set S which consists of all vectors of this form.

3467
04:50:33,000 --> 04:50:37,000
It's a subset of R3.

3468
04:50:37,000 --> 04:50:41,000
First component is two times some real number t.

3469
04:50:41,000 --> 04:50:50,000
Second component is zero and the third component is the negative of that real number t that we had up in the first component.

3470
04:50:50,000 --> 04:50:56,000
Okay, so how we want to know if S is a subspace of R3.

3471
04:50:56,000 --> 04:51:08,000
If we use the original method, that is to show that the three properties hold, then we would start with saying does S contain the zero vector.

3472
04:51:08,000 --> 04:51:17,000
And in this case, if we set t equal to zero, then we get zero, zero, zero.

3473
04:51:17,000 --> 04:51:23,000
And so the zero vector is contained in the set S.

3474
04:51:23,000 --> 04:51:29,000
We go to the next property as S closed under addition.

3475
04:51:29,000 --> 04:51:43,000
We need two generic vectors from S, so let's call those u and v, and u looks like two u, zero, negative u, and we'll say v is two v, zero, negative v.

3476
04:51:43,000 --> 04:51:51,000
And we need to add those together and see if the resulting vector is in the form that has to be an S.

3477
04:51:51,000 --> 04:51:59,000
So we add u and v and rearrange terms just a little bit and we end up with this vector here.

3478
04:51:59,000 --> 04:52:08,000
We've got two times u plus v on the first component, zero on the second component, negative u plus v in the third component.

3479
04:52:08,000 --> 04:52:17,000
And this is in the form that it needs to be to be in the set S because u plus v here is a real number.

3480
04:52:17,000 --> 04:52:23,000
We know that because these came from the vectors u and v.

3481
04:52:23,000 --> 04:52:30,000
So we have two times u plus v in the first component, negative u plus v in the last component, zero in the middle.

3482
04:52:30,000 --> 04:52:35,000
So it is in S. So S is closed under addition.

3483
04:52:35,000 --> 04:52:41,000
So we move on to the third property is S closed under scalar multiplication.

3484
04:52:41,000 --> 04:52:51,000
Well, again, we need a generic vector from the set S in a scalar, which we'll call C, and we compute C times u.

3485
04:52:51,000 --> 04:53:03,000
And again, rearranging terms a little bit, we can write it as two times cu in the first component, negative c times u in the last component, zero in the middle.

3486
04:53:03,000 --> 04:53:10,000
And since both c and u are real numbers, then c times u is a real number, so this vector is in S.

3487
04:53:10,000 --> 04:53:16,000
So we have all three properties satisfied, and therefore S is a subspace of R3.

3488
04:53:16,000 --> 04:53:19,000
Now there's a fair amount of work that went into that.

3489
04:53:19,000 --> 04:53:29,000
And so let's look at how we could use or if we could use this theorem to make the work a little easier.

3490
04:53:29,000 --> 04:53:37,000
All right, if we take a generic vector from the set S and we write it in parametric vector form.

3491
04:53:37,000 --> 04:53:40,000
So that means factor out the parameters.

3492
04:53:40,000 --> 04:53:49,000
In this case, there's only one t, and so we can write any vector in S as t times zero, two, zero, negative one.

3493
04:53:49,000 --> 04:53:54,000
So any vector in S is a multiple of this vector.

3494
04:53:54,000 --> 04:54:00,000
Therefore, S is equal to the span of this vector.

3495
04:54:00,000 --> 04:54:09,000
And since we've written S as the span of a finite set of vectors, that means by the theorem, S is a subspace of R3.

3496
04:54:09,000 --> 04:54:19,000
So you can see here that if your problem is one in which you can use this theorem, then it makes the work much easier.

