And to do that, we can write this generic vector in parametric vector form.

4452
06:19:59,000 --> 06:20:05,000
And so at this point, we know that these three vectors span our set S.

4453
06:20:06,000 --> 06:20:11,000
So we want to know, are they linearly independent?

4454
06:20:11,000 --> 06:20:14,000
And to check, see if they're linearly independent, we throw them in a matrix.

4455
06:20:14,000 --> 06:20:16,000
These are row operations.

4456
06:20:16,000 --> 06:20:21,000
Get that in echelon or reduced echelon form.

4457
06:20:21,000 --> 06:20:24,000
I got it in reduced echelon form.

4458
06:20:24,000 --> 06:20:29,000
And we can see here, there's not a pivot position in every column.

4459
06:20:29,000 --> 06:20:33,000
Therefore, they're not linearly independent.

4460
06:20:33,000 --> 06:20:37,000
We can see that there's a pivot position in the first two columns.

4461
06:20:37,000 --> 06:20:41,000
So that means that the first two vectors are linearly independent.

4462
06:20:41,000 --> 06:20:50,000
And notice that the negative one-third here means that the third column is minus one-third of the first column.

4463
06:20:50,000 --> 06:20:53,000
And if you look back, that is true.

4464
06:20:53,000 --> 06:20:56,000
Minus one-third of three is negative one.

4465
06:20:56,000 --> 06:21:01,000
Minus one-third of six is negative two and so forth.

4466
06:21:01,000 --> 06:21:03,000
All right.

4467
06:21:03,000 --> 06:21:07,000
So that means that we can throw out that third column.

4468
06:21:07,000 --> 06:21:11,000
And a basis for S would just consist of the first two vectors.

4469
06:21:11,000 --> 06:21:17,000
And once we have a basis, then we need to only count the vectors in the basis to get the dimension.

4470
06:21:17,000 --> 06:21:19,000
So there's two vectors in the basis.

4471
06:21:19,000 --> 06:21:21,000
That means the dimension of S is two.

4472
06:21:21,000 --> 06:21:33,000
And we don't say that S is R2, because it's not, because these vectors are in R4.

4473
06:21:33,000 --> 06:21:39,000
But what we do say is that S is a two-dimensional subspace of R4.

4474
06:21:39,000 --> 06:21:43,000
All right.

4475
06:21:43,000 --> 06:21:45,000
The basis theorem, this is an important theorem.

4476
06:21:45,000 --> 06:21:54,000
It says that if you have a vector space with dimension P, where P is greater than or equal to one, then the following conditions hold.

4477
06:21:54,000 --> 06:22:02,000
Number one, any linearly independent set of P elements in V is a basis for V.

4478
06:22:02,000 --> 06:22:03,000
Automatically.

4479
06:22:03,000 --> 06:22:05,000
Don't have to check to see if it spans.

4480
06:22:05,000 --> 06:22:12,000
Similarly, any set of P elements that spans V is automatically a basis.

4481
06:22:12,000 --> 06:22:18,000
Don't have to check to see if it's linearly independent.

4482
06:22:18,000 --> 06:22:26,000
Since we know the dimension of R3 is three, if you have a set of three vectors in R3 that are linearly independent, then you know they're a basis.

4483
06:22:26,000 --> 06:22:30,000
You don't have to check to see if they span, because they will.

4484
06:22:30,000 --> 06:22:36,000
Similarly, if you have a set of three vectors that span R3, then you know they're a basis for R3.

4485
06:22:36,000 --> 06:22:41,000
You don't have to check to see if they're linearly independent, because they will be.

4486
06:22:41,000 --> 06:22:47,000
So we basically end up with three pieces of the puzzle.

4487
06:22:47,000 --> 06:22:49,000
Let's go back to that.

4488
06:22:49,000 --> 06:22:59,000
Three pieces of the puzzle, knowing the dimension, having a set of that many vectors that spans, or having a set of that many vectors that's linearly independent.

4489
06:22:59,000 --> 06:23:10,000
If you have any two of those three pieces, then you can conclude that you have a basis for the vector space you're dealing with.

4490
06:23:10,000 --> 06:23:13,000
Okay.

4491
06:23:13,000 --> 06:23:18,000
For giving a matrix A, how do we find the dimension of the column space of A?

4492
06:23:18,000 --> 06:23:25,000
Well, we go back to our method, find a basis, and count the number of vectors in the basis.

4493
06:23:25,000 --> 06:23:31,000
Now let's think back, how do we find a basis for the column space of a matrix?

4494
06:23:31,000 --> 06:23:36,000
We will put A in echelon form so that we can find the pivot columns.

4495
06:23:36,000 --> 06:23:44,000
We pull those columns from A, not from the echelon form, but from the original matrix A, and that's our basis.

4496
06:23:44,000 --> 06:23:49,000
So here's one I think we looked at this one last time.

4497
06:23:49,000 --> 06:23:53,000
We take the matrix A, put it in echelon form.

4498
06:23:53,000 --> 06:24:03,000
We can see that the first, third, and fifth columns are pivot columns, so we pull the first, third, and fifth columns from A, and that's a basis for the column space of A.

4499
06:24:03,000 --> 06:24:13,000
And once you have a basis, then getting the dimensions trivial, three vectors in the basis, so the dimension of the column space of A is three.

4500
06:24:13,000 --> 06:24:23,000
In general, the dimension of the column space of a matrix is simply equal to the number of pivot columns in the matrix.

4501
06:24:23,000 --> 06:24:24,000
Alright, how about the null space?

4502
06:24:24,000 --> 06:24:30,000
We have a matrix A, how do we find the dimension of the null space of A?

4503
06:24:30,000 --> 06:24:34,000
Well, once again, find a basis and then count the number of vectors.

4504
06:24:34,000 --> 06:24:41,000
So let's think back, how do we find a basis for the null space of a matrix?

4505
06:24:41,000 --> 06:24:47,000
Well, we have to solve AX equals zero and write the solution in parametric vector form.

4506
06:24:47,000 --> 06:24:55,000
And the vectors that we get there both span the null space of A and they're linearly independent.

4507
06:24:55,000 --> 06:25:06,000
We made that argument last time that when you write those in parametric vector form, they will be linearly independent and therefore there'll be a basis for the null space of A.

4508
06:25:06,000 --> 06:25:19,000
So if we start with this matrix A, we solve AX equals zero and write the solution in parametric vector form.

4509
06:25:19,000 --> 06:25:38,000
So these two vectors are linearly independent, they span the null space, so there a basis for the null space.

4510
06:25:38,000 --> 06:25:44,000
Therefore the dimension of the null space for this particular matrix is two.

4511
06:25:44,000 --> 06:25:52,000
In general, the dimension of the null space is equal to the number of free variables in AX equals zero.

4512
06:25:52,000 --> 06:25:58,000
Because you have a vector here corresponding to each free variable.

4513
06:25:58,000 --> 06:26:01,000
And where do free variables come from?

4514
06:26:01,000 --> 06:26:04,000
They come from columns that don't have a pivot position.

4515
06:26:04,000 --> 06:26:10,000
So the dimension of the null space is equal to the number of non-pivot columns in A.

4516
06:26:10,000 --> 06:26:15,000
And recall the dimension of the column space is equal to the number of pivot columns.

4517
06:26:15,000 --> 06:26:19,000
Null space dimension is equal to the number of non-pivot columns.

4518
06:26:19,000 --> 06:26:27,000
So if we add those two quantities together, the dimension of the null space plus the dimension of the column space,

4519
06:26:27,000 --> 06:26:33,000
we get the number of pivot columns plus the number of non-pivot columns, which is equal to the number of columns.

4520
06:26:33,000 --> 06:26:38,000
And we'll hit on that some more next time.

4521
06:26:38,000 --> 06:26:44,380
Let's move on to talk about the rank of a matrix today.

4522
06:26:44,380 --> 06:26:46,820
Now first, a little bit of review.

4523
06:26:46,820 --> 06:26:50,480
Remember, the column space of a matrix

4524
06:26:50,480 --> 06:26:54,340
is the set of all linear combinations of the columns,

4525
06:26:54,340 --> 06:27:00,700
which is also the span of the set of columns of the matrix.

4526
06:27:00,700 --> 06:27:05,180
So we're going to talk about another subspace.

4527
06:27:05,180 --> 06:27:07,780
This time, the row space of a matrix.

4528
06:27:07,780 --> 06:27:09,740
So we know what the column space is,

4529
06:27:09,740 --> 06:27:13,660
so what do you think the row space of a matrix is?

4530
06:27:16,860 --> 06:27:22,180
Well, if you just take the analogous route,

4531
06:27:22,180 --> 06:27:26,060
then we get the row space of a matrix

4532
06:27:26,060 --> 06:27:29,020
is a set of all linear combinations of the rows

4533
06:27:29,020 --> 06:27:32,780
or the span of the set of rows of the matrix.

4534
06:27:32,780 --> 06:27:38,660
So it is truly just the analogous term to the column space.

4535
06:27:38,660 --> 06:27:41,820
We have the column space, all linear combinations of the columns,

4536
06:27:41,820 --> 06:27:46,220
row space, all linear combinations of the rows.

4537
06:27:46,220 --> 06:27:50,020
OK, so think back to find a basis for the column space

4538
06:27:50,020 --> 06:27:51,380
of a matrix.

4539
06:27:51,380 --> 06:27:53,260
We put the matrix initial on form

4540
06:27:53,260 --> 06:27:57,020
so that we can determine which columns are the pivot columns.

4541
06:27:57,020 --> 06:27:58,780
Then we go back to the original matrix

4542
06:27:58,780 --> 06:28:00,660
and pull out those columns, and that's

4543
06:28:00,660 --> 06:28:03,340
the basis for the column space of the original matrix.

4544
06:28:06,020 --> 06:28:08,460
So the question is, how do we find a basis for the row

4545
06:28:08,460 --> 06:28:10,020
space of a matrix?

4546
06:28:10,020 --> 06:28:13,180
And here, the similarities end somewhat,

4547
06:28:13,180 --> 06:28:16,620
although there still are some similarities.

4548
06:28:16,620 --> 06:28:20,180
But this theorem tells us how we can find a basis for the row

4549
06:28:20,180 --> 06:28:21,580
space of a matrix.

4550
06:28:21,580 --> 06:28:25,260
OK, so it says, if two matrices A and B are row equivalent,

4551
06:28:25,260 --> 06:28:27,840
so you can get from one to the other doing elementary row

4552
06:28:27,840 --> 06:28:32,280
operations, then their row spaces are the same.

4553
06:28:32,280 --> 06:28:36,480
Now you'll recall that that is not true for the column spaces.

4554
06:28:36,480 --> 06:28:38,680
When you do elementary row operations,

4555
06:28:38,680 --> 06:28:43,520
you may be changing the column space of the matrix.

4556
06:28:43,520 --> 06:28:46,400
But this theorem tells us that for row space,

4557
06:28:46,400 --> 06:28:50,200
that stays the same when you do row operations.

4558
06:28:50,200 --> 06:28:55,600
OK, if B is an echelon form, the non-zero rows of B

4559
06:28:55,600 --> 06:29:00,040
form a basis for the row space of A as well as for that of B.

4560
06:29:00,040 --> 06:29:04,200
So this tells us to find a basis for the row space of A.

4561
06:29:04,200 --> 06:29:09,040
We put it in echelon form and pull the non-zero rows

4562
06:29:09,040 --> 06:29:11,480
from that echelon form matrix.

4563
06:29:11,480 --> 06:29:15,840
And we have a basis for the row space of the original matrix

4564
06:29:15,840 --> 06:29:21,280
plus the echelon form matrix and any intermediate matrices

4565
06:29:21,280 --> 06:29:22,280
that we encountered.

4566
06:29:22,280 --> 06:29:32,200
OK, so again, elementary row operations do not change of this.

4567
06:29:32,200 --> 06:29:33,360
Back up here.

4568
06:29:33,360 --> 06:29:35,320
This is telling me that the linear dependence

4569
06:29:35,320 --> 06:29:37,280
relationships among the columns, OK?

4570
06:29:37,280 --> 06:29:39,480
So that means like if the second column of A

4571
06:29:39,480 --> 06:29:42,600
is 10 times the first column, then when

4572
06:29:42,600 --> 06:29:45,840
you do elementary row operations, that doesn't change.

4573
06:29:45,840 --> 06:29:47,680
So elementary row operations do not

4574
06:29:47,680 --> 06:29:50,040
change the linear dependence relationships

4575
06:29:50,080 --> 06:29:52,880
among the columns of a matrix.

4576
06:29:52,880 --> 06:29:56,360
However, they can change the linear dependence relationships

4577
06:29:56,360 --> 06:29:59,560
among the rows of a matrix.

4578
06:29:59,560 --> 06:30:02,480
OK, so let's look at a little simple example.

4579
06:30:02,480 --> 06:30:06,600
We start off with this matrix A. We do one row operation

4580
06:30:06,600 --> 06:30:10,640
and end up with this one, which I'll call B. Now, a basis

4581
06:30:10,640 --> 06:30:16,240
for the column space of A, we could just look at A

4582
06:30:16,240 --> 06:30:18,320
and say, well, I can see that the second column is

4583
06:30:18,320 --> 06:30:19,480
a multiple of the first.

4584
06:30:19,480 --> 06:30:22,280
So I throw it out and just keep the first column.

4585
06:30:22,280 --> 06:30:26,360
Or you could look at B and see where the pivot positions in B.

4586
06:30:26,360 --> 06:30:28,480
Well, there's only one in the first column.

4587
06:30:28,480 --> 06:30:32,520
So that means we want to pull the first column from A

4588
06:30:32,520 --> 06:30:38,120
to be a basis for the column space of A. If we want a basis

4589
06:30:38,120 --> 06:30:41,160
for the column space of B, that's straightforward

4590
06:30:41,160 --> 06:30:43,080
because B is already an echelon form.

4591
06:30:43,080 --> 06:30:46,160
So we know what the pivot columns are.

4592
06:30:46,160 --> 06:30:48,160
There's only one first column.

4593
06:30:48,160 --> 06:30:54,200
So that's a basis for the column space of B. So if we look

4594
06:30:54,200 --> 06:30:59,240
graphically at the column space of each of these matrices,

4595
06:30:59,240 --> 06:31:03,320
the red line here, you can see this vector right here.

4596
06:31:03,320 --> 06:31:04,680
This is 1, 1.

4597
06:31:04,680 --> 06:31:09,280
And so this red line is any multiple of the vector 1, 1.

4598
06:31:09,280 --> 06:31:14,720
So the red line is the column space of A. This vector here

4599
06:31:14,720 --> 06:31:16,600
is 1, 0.

