06:34:39,680 --> 06:34:43,680
And if you think about that just a little bit,

4657
06:34:43,680 --> 06:34:46,680
you can say, no, I don't think so,

4658
06:34:46,680 --> 06:34:49,680
because the dimension of the column space of A

4659
06:34:49,680 --> 06:34:53,680
is the number of pivot columns or pivot positions in A,

4660
06:34:53,680 --> 06:34:56,680
and that's when we look at B to figure that out,

4661
06:34:56,680 --> 06:34:59,680
but there's three pivot positions,

4662
06:34:59,680 --> 06:35:02,680
and the dimension of the row space of A

4663
06:35:02,680 --> 06:35:04,680
is also equal to the number of pivot positions,

4664
06:35:04,680 --> 06:35:08,680
because there's a pivot position in each non-zero row

4665
06:35:08,680 --> 06:35:12,680
in B here, or in an echelon form of A.

4666
06:35:12,680 --> 06:35:16,680
So each of these values is based off

4667
06:35:16,680 --> 06:35:18,680
of the number of pivot positions, right,

4668
06:35:18,680 --> 06:35:21,680
because a pivot position defines a pivot column,

4669
06:35:21,680 --> 06:35:25,680
and a pivot position defines a non-zero row.

4670
06:35:25,680 --> 06:35:29,680
So for any matrix, the dimension of the column space

