4790
06:44:30,860 --> 06:44:33,460
All right, and what if A is four by three?

4791
06:44:33,460 --> 06:44:38,760
What is the largest possible dimension of the row space?

4792
06:44:38,760 --> 06:44:52,160
All right, well, if A is four by three, then we could have at most three pivot positions, so at most three non-zero rows when we put it in echelon form.

4793
06:44:52,160 --> 06:45:00,760
So the maximum dimension of the row space is three.

4794
06:45:00,760 --> 06:45:07,560
All right, if A is three by four, what's the largest possible dimension of the row space?

4795
06:45:07,560 --> 06:45:14,360
Three by four, then again, the maximum number of pivot positions we can have is three.

4796
06:45:14,360 --> 06:45:22,860
So we have at most three non-zero rows, so the maximum dimension of the row space is three.

4797
06:45:22,860 --> 06:45:24,960
How about if A is six by four?

4798
06:45:24,960 --> 06:45:28,760
What is the smallest possible dimension of the null space?

4799
06:45:28,760 --> 06:45:38,360
That's asking what's the smallest number of free variables you can have, or what's the smallest number of non-pivot columns you could have?

4800
06:45:38,360 --> 06:45:52,160
Well, since we have more rows than columns, every column could be a pivot column, in which case there's no free variables, and so the minimum dimension of the null space of A would be zero.

